As we do not possess anything but fragments of the New

Comedy, from which the Roman dramatists borrowed, it is impossible to estimate the amount of originality, which belongs

to any play of Plautus taken as a whole3 but the ease and vigour of his language would show clearly that he was treating his models with some freedom, if this fact were not also evident from the numerous Roman allusions, to which reference has already been made.
